<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62736" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62736">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62736">
(
<bibRefCitation author="Day, J. H." journalOrPublisher="British Museum (Natural History), London" pageId="0" pageNumber="62736" refId="B6422044" refString="Day, J. H., 1967. A monograph on the Polychaeta of southern Africa. Part. 1. Errantia. British Museum (Natural History), London" title="A monograph on the Polychaeta of southern Africa. Part. 1. Errantia" year="1967">Day 1967a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Paxton, Hannelore" journalOrPublisher="Zoosymposia" pageId="0" pageNumber="62736" pagination="241 - 264" refId="B6423113" refString="Paxton, Hannelore, 2009. Phylogeny of Eunicida (Annelida) based on morphology of jaws. Zoosymposia 2 (1): 241 - 264" title="Phylogeny of Eunicida (Annelida) based on morphology of jaws" volume="2" year="2009">Paxton 2009</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Uebelacker, Joan M." journalOrPublisher="Minerals Management Service. Barry A. Vittor &amp; Associates, Inc." pageId="0" pageNumber="62736" refId="B6426994" refString="Uebelacker, Joan M., Johnson, Paul G., 1984. Taxonomic guide to the polychaetes of the Northern Gulf of Mexico. Minerals Management Service. Barry A. Vittor &amp; Associates, Inc." title="Taxonomic guide to the polychaetes of the Northern Gulf of Mexico" year="1984">Uebelacker and Johnson 1984</bibRefCitation>
): Prostomium with four eyes, without appendages (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStartId="F6439127" pageId="0" pageNumber="62736">3</figureCitation>
<figureCitation captionStartId="F6439138" pageId="0" pageNumber="62736">f</figureCitation>
). Jaws prionognath-type with maxillary parts like scissors with blades (
<normalizedToken originalValue="“carriers”">&quot;carriers&quot;</normalizedToken>
). Formula (maxillae): 1+9, 8+14, 7+5, 1+4 and 1+1. Anterior notopodial cirri longer than posterior ones. Neuropodia carry pre- and post-chaetal lobes; serrated winged capillaries and yellow acicula.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
